But let's go back a bit. Nobody asks: "What exactly is inside?"
At the top is one of these ESP32 camera boards with a fisheye lens and an IR LED that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The reason for the strange shape of this plastic box is the swiveling side wall of the nest box. I bought it in this form and could not change it, so I had to build around it.
Since there is no power in the garden, the entire thing is powered by a solar panel and a 2600 mAh 18650 battery.
I didn't photograph the battery or the charger, but here is a picture of the panel.
In the gray box that hangs on the side of the nest box, the battery is located.
If it is charged, I have a runtime of about 4 hours.
That's what I call a feature. This way, the birds also get some privacy.
At first, I wasn't sure if the internet in our garden would be sufficient for this setup. The old access points that I replaced last autumn in the fall would not have been enough.
But the new ones cover this area very well.
It's almost a shame because I had planned to install a TP-Link cpe210 on the roof and direct it downwards into the garden.
